To Cook,<br>
First of all, I would like to comment on some of the things you posted recently.<br><br>
I can see you point and understand your views.  First of all, the topic of this thread is lessons of the Vietnam War.  The very best lesson in my opinion is not to get involved in wars that have no direct interest to American security.  Vietnam was a war we should have NEVER gotten involved in.  I became totally convinced of this point when I visited the Veterans Memorial in Washington DC in 1992, the 10th Anniversary of it being built.  I saw veterans in tears over the loss of friends, I saw Gold Star Mothers still asking why their sons died, I saw a group of people still struggling to find meaning in it all.  I then became convinced that America has no place in fighting, unless there are clear goals, and a purpose.  Vietnam has meaning to those who served and did what they could to help the Vietnamese people, but it served no other purpose for this nation than to divide us and create wounds that may never heal.<br>
In regards to Kuwait, which you pointed out as a example, I am under the distinct opinion (having known many Desert Storm vets), that our involvement there was mainly for the protection and recapture of the oilfields (Kuwait has the oil rich Bergen oil fields).  Yes, we freed the Kuwaiti people (it is a shame they don't have many personal freedoms under the Emir), but we also rebuilt the oilfields.  In a editorial in the USA Today, the head of the organization of American oil companies stated that the real reason the war was fought was to protect oil for first world countries.  Desert Storm and Vietnam are different fights.  The best part of Desert Storm was America's respect for the returning soldier.  No doubt in part to the efforts of Vietnam Veterans, who did not want to see this country disrespect another group of decent young Americans.  Also, if the rights of people in the Persian Gulf are so important, why didn't we intervene in the war between North and South Yemen, just a few years back?<br><br>
Cook, your Charles Manson and McVeigh examples don't apply, since we talking about international affairs and not the actions of sick animals in our own society.  The law needs to prevent that and Americans have to become more aware of Animals like these.<br><br>
My main point is this, I WOULD BE THE FIRST ONE TO CARRY A SIGN AND PROTEST RATHER THAN SEE ANOTHER WAR LIKE VIETNAM.<br>
Forget about the others &quot;spilling their blood thing&quot;, tell me some good reasons why American should have NOT let Vietnam fight its own war (with perhaps food and medical aid).  Vietnam and China were not going to invade the US.  I understand your view that why engage in Vietnam and not else where.  I don't know?  Perhaps this country has learned a painful lesson.<br><br>
I agree that Washington put us there, and if more of the sons of leaders had served it would have been over more quickly.  But here is my question, WHY DOES THE USA HAVE TO BE A WORLD POLICEMAN?  I agree we have to aid in efforts to destroy terrorism and to protect our solid Nato allies, but why get involved in every fight, especially those that have no impact on our country?   I am of the opinion, that we should provide aid to countries in need (humanitarian nature), but I believe that countries are entitled to their own wars and civil wars (How would the US have felt if England joined the Confederacy during the Civil War?)<br><br>
Please understand that there should never be another Vietnam.  That is the best lesson here.  I love America and I deeply respect the people who defend it, escpecially Nam vets.  I feel it is the duty of every peron to make sure America stays out of fights that are not ours.  It is also our duty to treat all veterans with the best respect possible.  (Even though I love space exploration, too bad the US didn't spend the money used to send a probe to study Mars rocks on treating PTSD or providing aid to vets out of jobs!!!)<br><br>
By the way Cook, in another thread you mention how you laughed your heads when the VC blew up the Liberty Bridge.  As a writer and historian, I am here to tell you that the VC sapper who got the bridge, bought his scuba gear in a MARINE post exchange in Danang.  Security in Vietnam is very difficult, and I can give you at leat 10 examples of VC/NVA breeching the defenses of both Army and Marine bases, so don't criticize the Seabees  The bridge was and still is considered one the best in Vietnam.  The Seabees had the honor of building the biggest bridge built by any American engineers in Vietnam.  Also, the damage to the bridge couldn't be too bad, since it was repaired in a record 32 hours (I know men who served there).<br><br>
As for poor Corpsman and self inflicted wounds among Marines and Navy, I took this topic up with as many local Marine and Navy Vietnam vets in my area, NONE remembered bad Corpsman lasting in the field or any self-inflicted wounds.  Maybe it was something in your unit.  The Corpsman in my Dad's unit was treated with the highest respect.  His title of &quot;Doc&quot; came with admiration for a job well done.  I sorry you had a bad one.  There was no place for bad Corpsman.  I question the commander that left him in place.
